## Add BlurAsync API for ElementReference:

Add a BlurAsync API to ElementReference in Blazor to allow components to programmatically remove focus from an HTML element. This enhancement aligns with the existing FocusAsync API and exposes a native browser capability (element.blur()) through a first-class Blazor abstraction. The original request started as FocusOutAsync, but the discussion clarified that the appropriate browser primitive is blur(). #28127

## Motivation and goals

- Provide a simple and discoverable way to remove focus from an element without requiring custom JavaScript interop.
- Maintain consistency with the existing FocusAsync functionality available on ElementReference.
- Expose only browser-native behavior instead of introducing new focus-management semantics not supported by HTML.
- Reduce repetitive JS interop code for common scenarios such as blurring an input after form submission or Enter key processing.

## In scope

- Add a new BlurAsync extension method for ElementReference.
- Invoke the native DOM element.blur() behavior through Blazor’s existing JS interop infrastructure.
- Support Blazor Server, WebAssembly, and other rendering models that already support ElementReference operations.
- Follow the same usage pattern and developer experience as FocusAsync.

## Out of scope

- Adding a FocusOutAsync API based on focus event semantics instead of exposing the browser's native blur() functionality.
- Automatically moving focus to another element after blur is invoked, as focus transitions remain browser controlled.

## Risks / unknowns

- Browser behavior after blur() may differ depending on the currently focused element and document state.
- Applications relying on focus-related events may observe additional blur or focusout event execution when adopting the API.
- Calling BlurAsync before the element is rendered may result in the same limitations that apply to other ElementReference operations.
- Some accessibility workflows may depend on focus retention, so developers must use the API appropriately.

## API Surface

```
    /// <summary>
    /// Removes focus from an element given its <see cref="ElementReference"/>.
    /// </summary>
    /// <param name="elementReference">A reference to the element to remove focus from.</param>
    /// <returns>The <see cref="ValueTask"/> representing the asynchronous blur operation.</returns>
    public static ValueTask BlurAsync(this ElementReference elementReference)
```

## Edge Case Scenarios

- Element not rendered yet : Calling BlurAsync before the element reference is established should behave consistently with other ElementReference APIs and may fail if the underlying element is unavailable.
- Element already not focused: The operation should complete successfully without any visible effect.
- Element removed from DOM: If the target element no longer exists, the operation may result in the same runtime behavior currently observed for invalid element references.
- Focus moves automatically: Some browsers may transfer focus to another focusable element or the document body after blur is executed.

## Examples

```
<input @ref="searchBox" @onkeydown="HandleKeyDown" />

@code {
    private ElementReference searchBox;
   private async Task HandleKeyDown(KeyboardEventArgs e)
   {
      if (e.Key == "Enter")
      {
           await searchBox.BlurAsync();
       }
    }
}
```

